<promed@promedmail.org>

[More than 70 pathogens are classified in the order Flaviviridae. The
word "flavi" is from "flavus", a Latin word meaning "yellow", because the
type species of flavivirus is yellow fever virus.

I tend to agree with Jack Woodall, ProMED Moderator and an expert in this
field, that Cordoba is beyond the yellow fever belt. This outbreak is more
likely to be due to Rocio virus, or given the age spectrum, even West Nile
virus. Among the other flaviviruses are the agents causing dengue fever
(types 1, 2, 3 & 4), St. Louis encephalitis, Japanese encephalitis, Murray
Valley or Kunjin, tick-borne encephalitis, Kyasanur Forest disease, Omsk
hemorrhagic fever, louping ill, Powassan, and hepatitis C.

Of these, West Nile virus is most closely related to St. Louis encephalitis
virus, cases of which predate West Nile fever cases in the USA, which have
only been seen there for the past 6 years since 1999. West Nile virus may
infect humans, mosquitoes, birds, horses, and certain other mammals.

The Argentinean health authorities are currently searching for a specific
viral agent responsible for the outbreak of flaviviral encephalitis and the
related mosquito vectors. They are also investigating whether birds and
other mammals are involved. ProMED requests further information from anyone
familiar with the situation in that area. - Mod.RY]

[On 5 Apr 2005 this same source ran a story which included the sentence: "In
the 1st 3 months of this year [2005], Cordoba registered 32 cases of the so-
called St Louis encephalitis." It will be recalled that the 1st cases of
West Nile virus in the USA (in 1999) were intially misdiagnosed by
laboratory testing as St Louis encephalitis. A check of the Spanish language
website today does not show any more recent report. - Mod.JW]
